Project: Investigate a Dataset (FBI Gun Data)¶

The purpose of this project is to explore the trends of U.S gun purchases with census population data.

  • [You can find this project repository in my my github repository]

Introduction¶

(original source on Github)

  • The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System.
  • The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives.
  • Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isn’t otherwise ineligible to make a purchase.
  • The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov.

NICS Firearm Background Checks:¶

  • Month and Year by State and Type
  • The types of firearms are defined by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives as follows:
    • Handgun
      • any firearm which has a short stock and is designed to be held and fired by the use of a single hand;
    • Long Gun
      • a weapon designed or redesigned, made or remade, and intended to be fired from the shoulder, and designed or redesigned and made or remade to use the energy of the explosive in
    • Other
      • refers to frames, receivers, and other firearms that are neither handguns nor long guns (rifles or shotguns),
      • such as firearms having a pistol grip that expel a shotgun shell, or National Firearms Act firearms, including silencers.
    • multiple
      • The indication of “multiple” denotes a background check where more than one type of firearm is associated to a single background check and “admin” denotes the administrative checks that are for other authorized uses of the NICS.
    • Pre-Pawn
      • requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees seeking to pledge or pawn a firearm as security for the payment or repayment of money, prior to actually pledging or pawning the firearm.
    • Redemption—background checks
      • requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to regain possession of a firearm after pledging or pawning a firearm as security at a pawn shop.
    • Returned/Disposition—background checks
      • requested by criminal justice/law enforcement agencies prior to returning a firearm in its possession to the respective transferee, to ensure the individual is not prohibited.
    • Rentals—background checks
      • requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm when the firearm is loaned or rented for use off the premises of the business.
    • Private Sale—background checks
      • requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm from a private party seller who is not an officially-licensed FFL.
    • Return to Seller-Private Sale—background checks
      • requested by an officially-licensed FFL on prospective firearm transferees attempting to possess a firearm from a private party seller who is not an officially-licensed FFL.

Data Wrangling:¶

1- Gathering¶

  • https://github.com/BuzzFeedNews/nics-firearm-background-checks/blob/master/data/nics-firearm-background-checks.csv
  • The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file. It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type.
  • The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file. It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year.
    • https://d17h27t6h515a5.cloudfront.net/topher/2017/November/5a0a5623_ncis-and-census-data/ncis-and-census-data.zip
  • The U.S. census data is found in a .csv file. It contains population at the state level from (2010) to (2019)
  • Resulting three files:
    1- [us_census_data.csv]
    2- [us_census_population.csv]
    3- [nics-firearm-background-checks.csv]

2- Assessing & Cleaning¶

  • Assessing Data The issues you identified were:

    • Nondescriptive column headers
    • Missing values (i.e. NaNs)
    • Inconsistent representations of values

  • data Assessing divided to in three script for each gathed data

    • [01-nics.ipynb]
    • [02-population.ipynb]
    • [03-census.ipynb]
  • Resulting three files:
    1- [nics.csv]
    2- [population.csv]
    3- [census.csv]
  • A messy (i.e. untidy) dataset
    • noted [census.csv] dataset is un structured and not easy to ooperate in
    • we divided this dataset with common related dates and its data using [04-Create_data.ipynb]
  • Resulting files:
    1- [census_2010_2016.csv]
    2- [census_2012.csv]
    3- [census_2014_2015.csv]
    4- [census_2015.csv]
    5- [census_2016.csv]
    6- [census_July_2016.csv]

Display correlation matrix (r):¶

  • Correlation coefficients are used to measure the strength of the linear relationship between two variables.
  • A linear correlation coefficient that is greater than zero indicates a positive relationship.
  • A value that is less than zero signifies a negative relationship.
  • Finally, a value of zero indicates no relationship between the two variables x and y.
  • KEY TAKEAWAYS:
    • A value of zero indicates no relationship between the two variables being compared.
    • A negative correlation, or inverse correlation.

Plotting Function for plotting correlation matrix with each columns in dataset¶

In [8]:
def plt_corr_matrix(corrMatrix, title):
    # Sample figsize in inches
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))    
    ax = sns.heatmap(corrMatrix.round(2),  vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0, cmap=sns.diverging_palette(20, 220, n=200), square=True, annot=True, ax=ax1)
    ax.set_xticklabels( ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, horizontalalignment='right');
    ax.set_title('"Correlation matrix (r) for {}"'.format(title), fontsize=12)
    ax.xaxis.set_ticks_position('bottom')
    ax.xaxis.set_label_position('top')
    ax.legend()

From the above plot of correlation matrix between columns of NICS Firearm Background Checks:

  • There is no negative value of correlation coefficients, i.e. there is no negative 'at least' relationship between data
  • There is a strong linear relationship between number of permits and total number of fire equipment
  • apparently there is no relationship between this five columns "permit", "handgun", "long_gun", "other", "multiple"
  • Apparently all relationships between "totals" and other remaining columns
  • That is why we could say that column "totals" can represents the data set

Using Cumulative Sum¶

  • A cumulative sum is a sequence of partial sums of a given sequence.
  • For example, the cumulative sums of the sequence {a,b,c,...}, are a, a+b, a+b+c, ....
  • It is typically used for monitoring change detection.
In [174]:
# create a cumulative dataset for gun types over years from 2010 - 2019
df1 = nics_df.drop(columns=['year','state','permit','totals']).groupby(['month']).sum().cumsum().reset_index().sort_values(by='month')

In [297]:
flag = 0
for state in list(df1.state.unique()):
    df0 = df1[df1['state'] == state]
    df0 = df0.iloc[:,2:].pct_change().replace(np.nan,0).replace(np.inf,1).round(3)[1:].describe()[1:2].reset_index()    
    df0['index'] = state    
    if (flag == 0):
        pct_change_df = df0
        flag = 1
    elif(flag >= 1):
        # merge two dtat set with base index 'state','mean', join="inner"
        # to append df2 at the end of df1 dataframe
        #pct_change_df.append(df0)
        pct_change_df = pd.concat([pct_change_df, df0])

def corrMatrix_df(df):
    # To find the correlation among the columns of df1 and df2 along the column axis
    if 'year' in df.columns:    
        df1 = df.drop(columns=['totals','year'],axis=1).corrwith(df['totals'], axis = 0).round(2)
    else :
        df1 = df.drop(columns=['totals'],axis=1).corrwith(df['totals'], axis = 0).round(2)
    df1 = df1.reset_index()
    df1.columns = ["index", 'r']    
    return df1
